    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2469392908" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2469392908" />
    <a title="Whiskey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/79191615-whiskey"><img alt="Whiskey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1521523346p2/79191615.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2469392908?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Whiskey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Whiskey" href="/user/show/79191615-whiskey">Whiskey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781844088959" href="/book/show/17356826-in-diamond-square">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2469392908" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13201937569548519269">Rodoreda reveals the religion of endurance through the eyes of a Catalan woman whose life and land are beset by war and famine and misogyny. Through little domestic victories and defeats, Natalia sees the light and shadows of marriage; children; cleaning; working; cooking. She observes the natural world closely but also has mystical visions of swirling colors, sounds, and smells. She meets Joe, her first husband, at a festival in Barcelona&apos;s Diamond Square (thus the title). Joe renames Natalia, </span>
  <span id="freeText13201937569548519269" style="display:none">Rodoreda reveals the religion of endurance through the eyes of a Catalan woman whose life and land are beset by war and famine and misogyny. Through little domestic victories and defeats, Natalia sees the light and shadows of marriage; children; cleaning; working; cooking. She observes the natural world closely but also has mystical visions of swirling colors, sounds, and smells. She meets Joe, her first husband, at a festival in Barcelona's Diamond Square (thus the title). Joe renames Natalia, "Pigey" --as in pigeon (not piggy) but more poetically if less accurately rendered in a previous translation as "Dovey."<br /><br />Natalia closely observes life and she finds inspiration, instruction, wisdom and the grand metaphor of existence. <i>"I watched the waves coming and going, always the same, the same...all in a rush to come and go. I sat looking out at the sea that was sometimes grey, sometimes green, blue more than anything else, that expanse of moving, living water, water that talked, my thoughts drained away and I was left empty.</i> "On the terrace, with breeze and the blue sky all around me...I felt as if I'd been drained empty again and was being pumped back up by something very peculiar. Her husband Joe accuses, "What's wrong with you?<br /><br />Joe neglects carpentry to concoct grand schemes involving carrier pigeons, but Natalia does all the dirty work. The stench of an incubated egg or chick makes her retch, and her skin reeks of the pigeons. She unconsciously sees herself in the pigeons. The birds of loneliness are as trapped as Natalia. Along with the pigeons comes a funnel--the relevance of which will not be clear until later chapters. <br /><br />The Pigeons, like people, create shadow and light; they too are jealous and dislike strangers. Natalia sabotages her husband's pigeons in silent protest against the patriarchy, while Catalans revolt against the conquering Nationalists during the Spanish Civil War. "What was brewing came." And when it comes, it reminds me of Pigey's grisly memories of the mercado: bodies slit open; sopping with blood; canals clogged with clotted blood; and plugs of black blood. <br /><br />This quiet novel never explains or names the Spanish Civil War.<i>"It was so sad we lovers of peace and happiness had had to get mixed up in this particular slice of history. Better to read about history in books than to write it in bullets."</i> A foreboding pigeon returns with her neck feathers wet from the sweat of death. "All feather and bones." Executions have replaced wedding celebrations in Diamond Square.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Suffering from PTSD and delayed grief, Natalia despairs and plots suicide and the mercy-killing of her children-- like the pigeon eggs that she sabotaged as an act of resistance against her selfish and oppressive husband before the war. Yet, on her way to buy acid to funnel down their throats, Natalia follows a lady carrying a candle in the rain into a church where Natalia has a vision rising with incense. Little balls float like bubbles above the altar and form a mountain beside it. She smells blood, the smell of death, mixing with the incense, and she hears angry angels who warn of the presence of the slain. God is angry with the slaughter. <i>"Fly high, Pidgey, fly high. The grief of this world is after you."</i> She buys the acid on credit from Anthony, the birdseed grocer who reminds her of a kind boyfriend. New life presents itself to Natalia after she meets Anthony. She remarries and begins again. With love, all things are possible. She returns to the parks to observe flowers, leaves, buds, pigeons, and raindrops. She waxes nostalgic to other ladies in the park about the 40 pairs of pigeons that she once hated but now misses.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />She finds the sacraments of the natural world. Inside each puddle of water, she sees the reflection of a vast blue sky. Natalia teaches happiness and contentment after defeat. Perhaps we fail to achieve our dreams, but the crown of victory comes from enduring defeat and in finding and celebrating the sky wishing the puddles of misery, which reflect possibility. "My dear, these things are life." But we can endure defeat without vanquishment. <br /><br />****<br /><br />Details of Interest to Me. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ AUTHOR: Merc√© Rodoreda (1908-1983). During the civil war, she worked for the government of Catalonia. She sought exile in France during Franco‚Äôs reign but died in Girona. She is considered the greatest modern writer of Catalonia.<br /><br />TRANSLATION: Translator Peter Bush uses simple English and Catalan name equivalents; doves are pigeons. <br /><br />PUBLISHER: Virago Modern Classics dedicates its label to the celebration of women writers and to rediscovery and reprinting of their work.<br /><br />TITLE: Named after the square in Barcelona where the main character met her first husband and in which her daughter was married. An earlier English title was translated as ‚ÄúThe Time of the Doves.‚Äù Doves v. Pigeons: Pigeons are not doves, though they come from same family. <br /><br />EPIGRAPH: "My dear, these things are life." (Meredith)<br /><br />FIRST SENTENCE: ‚ÄúJulie came to the cake-shop just to tell me they would be raffling coffeepots before they got to the lucky posy; she'd see them and they were lovely, an orange split in two, showing its pips, painted on a white background. "<br /><br />LAST SENTENCE: Inside each puddle, however small, there would be a sky...the sky a bird sometimes disturbed...a thirsty bird disturbing the sky unawares with water from its beak...or shrieking out of the foliage like flashes of lightning, several birds would swoop down for a quick bath in the puddle, ruffling their feathers and then wiping the mud, their beaks and their wings all over the sky. Happy..."<br /><br />MOTIFS: pigeons, Locust painting (Apocalypse); woodworms; tapeworms; scales; market; blood; flowers; belly buttons; blackbirds, black blood, bluebottle flies (Satan); cloud envelopment; drizzling rain slowly stretching down objects that it strikes; umbilical cords and belly buttons; strawberry sky at twilight, cork; dolls; smells; visions; bubbles; balls; sea colors; rats; intestines; moss (staying home).<br /><br />LITERARY INFLUENCES: Rodoreda echoes the terse style of Hemingway. Characters: Anthony- impotent character (Jake in "The Sun Also Rises"); Spanish Civil War ("For Whom The Bells Toll"); concrete details ("Farewell to Arms"). Unlike Hemingway, who wrote of war, sports, fishing, boxing, bullfighting--Rodoreda writes of the domestic world. <br /><br />SYMBOLS<br />stretching rain (drainpipes, glass, feathers; not wanting to let go); pigeons (trapped); cork (survival by paring down); blood (death); conch (church); pearl (priest); ; moss (staying home);<br /><br />METAPHORS: <br />Some readers prefer to see as another feminist tale focusing on the perpetual abuse of women by men. I see more universal themes that speak to all genders. While Natalia is representative of Catalan identity, she also becomes a heroine for all who survive defeat to find new life in the little things. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="13201937569548519269" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


