<div id="review_1578122118" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1578122118" />
    <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera"><img alt="Inderjit Sanghera" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564826235p2/900800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1578122118?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Inderjit Sanghera" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera">Inderjit Sanghera</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1578122118" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13111876846047723728">It would be misleading-and slightly disingenuous-no label the narrator as ‚Äúsimplistic‚Äù; the word has such negative connotations and does not reflect the complexity of Natalia‚Äôs journey, through a life of love, war, death and loss; emotional complexity should not wholly be defined powers of articulation, but by the development of a character‚Äôs inner life and Natalia, who does the best with the hand dealt with her by life, is able to stubbornly over-come all of the hard-ships, from abject poverty </span>
  <span id="freeText13111876846047723728" style="display:none">It would be misleading-and slightly disingenuous-no label the narrator as ‚Äúsimplistic‚Äù; the word has such negative connotations and does not reflect the complexity of Natalia‚Äôs journey, through a life of love, war, death and loss; emotional complexity should not wholly be defined powers of articulation, but by the development of a character‚Äôs inner life and Natalia, who does the best with the hand dealt with her by life, is able to stubbornly over-come all of the hard-ships, from abject poverty to a macho, troglodyte husband to war and starvation and finally find happiness and solace lying against the back of a kindly cripple-as Rodoreda states, Natalia may not have the finesses or grace of Anna Karenina or Madame Bovary, but her life is imbued with a deeper wisdom, and unlike Anna or Emma, she is able to triumph over life and not be overcome by it despite, objectively speaking, going through far worse.<br /><br />The novel is told via stream-of-consciousness via Natalie; indeed the whole world is seen through the prism of her mind, from the civil war, where she exists on the periphery and only occasionally seeing the despondent and demoralized soldiers who visit interminably, to her children, or her relationship with the many men who love her; her first husband, the domineering Joe, his friend Matthew and her second husband, the kindly shop-keeper Anthony. Indeed her relationship with Anthony acts as the turning point in her narrative style; gone are the naive, somewhat saccharine thoughts which pass through her mind and which are largely responsible for the accusations of simplicity, freeing herself (though not wholly) from the shackles of Joe, she slowly regains her sense of identity, her sense of purpose, via the unselfish love of Anthony, via his kindness-despite the tragic back-drop of the story the core theme is the evolution of Natalie-unlike Emma Bovary and-to a lesser extent Anna Karenina, Natalie is able to find solace in love; not as a grand passion or emotion, but via the simple beat of her husband‚Äôs heart on a cold night in Barcelona.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13111876846047723728" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
