<div id="review_1533931284" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1533931284" />
    <a title="Taube" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3268083-taube"><img alt="Taube" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1378557224p2/3268083.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1533931284?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Taube" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Taube" href="/user/show/3268083-taube">Taube</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1533931284" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9723832875560656392">&quot;[I] read [The Time of the Doves] cover to cover all in one afternoon. When I was finished, I felt as foolish as Balboa discovering the powerful Pacific.&quot; --Sandra Cisneros<br/><br/>In Sandra Cisneros&apos; recent memoir, &quot;A House of My Own: Stories from My Life,&quot; Cisneros speaks of an ebullient admiration for the writing of the Catalan writer Merc√® Rodoreda. Cisneros is hardly alone in her respect for Rodoreda-- Gabriel Garc√≠a M√°rquez has also modestly described &quot;The Time of the Doves&quot; (La pla√ßa del Diamant) </span>
  <span id="freeText9723832875560656392" style="display:none">"[I] read [The Time of the Doves] cover to cover all in one afternoon. When I was finished, I felt as foolish as Balboa discovering the powerful Pacific." --Sandra Cisneros<br /><br />In Sandra Cisneros' recent memoir, "A House of My Own: Stories from My Life," Cisneros speaks of an ebullient admiration for the writing of the Catalan writer Merc√® Rodoreda. Cisneros is hardly alone in her respect for Rodoreda-- Gabriel Garc√≠a M√°rquez has also modestly described "The Time of the Doves" (La pla√ßa del Diamant) as "The most beautiful novel published in Spain since the Civil War."<br /><br />Reading Cisneros's recommendation made me want to read this in an emphatic way. (That, and the fact that my own name means "dove" in German also provided a kind of linguistic/spiritual nudge.)<br /><br />And so, to discover that my own experience of this novel somewhat mirrored that of Cisneros. Except that, instead of reading it within the space of a single afternoon "under the sun in the courtyard in Berkeley, California on the hottest day of autumn, 1988" I read this over the space of an afternoon on a cold and grey February day in New York, 2016. <br /><br />To read and read, in that greedy and voracious way that people do when they instantly connect with writing in that blazing"OMG this is freaking awesome" sort of way. As Cisneros writes: "Roderoda writes about feelings, about characters so numbed or overwhelmed by events they have only emotions as language... (she is) adept at listening to those who do not speak, who are filled with great emotions, albeit mute to name them."<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9723832875560656392" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


